= Change the User Interface Language =
== Introduction ==
The system language used in Whonix is easily changed. The technical steps are identical to the Debian method because Whonix is based on Debian GNU/Linux and KDE. Users can also refer to Debian or KDE upstream documentation. Native English speakers do not need to make any changes.

== System ==
=== All Languages ===
Open a terminal.

<code>Start menu</code> -> <code>Applications</code> -> <code>System</code> -> <code>Terminal</code>

[[Update]] the package lists.

{{CodeSelect|code=
sudo apt-get update
}}

Search for available language packs.

{{CodeSelect|code=
apt-cache search kde-i18n
}}

Or [http://packages.debian.org/search?keywords=kde-l10n&searchon=names&suite=stable&section=all search the Debian package archive].

Install a language pack. In the example below, replace <i>-ar</i> with the preferred language.

{{CodeSelect|code=
sudo apt-get install kde-l10n-ar
}}

Change the KDE setting.

<code>Start menu</code> -> <code>Applications</code> -> <code>System</code> -> <code>System Settings</code> -> <code>Locale</code> -> <code>Languages</code> -> <code>Change Language</code>

=== Russian ===
Open a terminal.

<code>Start menu</code> -> <code>Applications</code> -> <code>System</code> -> <code>Terminal.</code>

Reconfigure locales.

{{CodeSelect|code=
sudo dpkg-reconfigure locales
}}

From the list of enabled and available locales, uncheck/disable everything except for English and Russian.

<pre>
en_US.UTF-8 UTF-8
ru_RU.UTF-8 UTF-8
</pre>

Note: If any other locales are enabled, <i>???????</i> (question mark) characters will appear instead of Cyrillic script when typing in the terminal.

Reboot Whonix-Workstation for the changes to take effect.

=== Korean ===
Note: The steps below were originally outlined in the [https://sourceforge.net/p/whonix/discussion/general/thread/fff34595/ Whonix forums] by an anonymous poster. That thread can be used for follow-up support questions.

Open a terminal.

<code>Start menu</code> -> <code>Applications</code> -> <code>System</code> -> <code>Terminal</code>

Update the package lists.

{{CodeSelect|code=
sudo apt-get update
}}

View the available language packs.

{{CodeSelect|code=
apt-cache search kde-i18n
}}

Install the Korean language pack.

{{CodeSelect|code=
sudo apt-get install kde-l10n-ko
}}

Install Korean fonts.

{{CodeSelect|code=
sudo apt-get install ttf-unfonts-core ttf-unfont-extra
}}

Open system settings and set <code>eungulim</code> as KDE's font.

Open a terminal and reconfigure locales.

{{CodeSelect|code=
sudo dpkg-reconfigure locales
}}

Set <code>ko KR.UTF-8 UTF-8</code> as the default locale.

Install nabi.

{{CodeSelect|code=
apt-get install nabi
}}

Restart the Whonix-Workstation and start nabi. The Korean script is now available system-wide for writing and reading.

== Tor Browser ==
=== Introduction ===
Using <u>one</u> of these methods is sufficient to change the language in [[Tor Browser]].

=== Method 1: Config File Method ===
Complete these steps in the Whonix-Workstation.

Available Tor Browser languages as of April 2017:

* Arabic (ar)
* German (de)
* English (en-US)
* Spanish (es-ES)
* Persian/Farsi (fa)
* French (fr)
* Italian (it)
* Japanese (ja)
* Korean (ko)
* Dutch (nl)
* Polish (pl)
* Brazilian Portuguese (pt-BR)
* Russian (ru)
* Turkish (tr)
* Vietnamese (vi)
* Chinese (zh-CN)


To check if further languages are supported, visit: https://www.torproject.org/dist/torbrowser/. 

Binaries and supported language packs are listed by Tor Browser version. The nomenclature for language packs is classified according to [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_ISO_639-1_codes|ISO 639-1 codes].

{{Open with root rights|filename=
/etc/torbrowser.d/50_user.conf
}}

And add for example.

{{CodeSelect|code=
TB_LANG="vi"
}}

Replace <code>vi</code> with <code>zh-CN</code> for Chinese and so on.

Save.

After changing this setting, use [[Tor_Browser#Tor_Browser_Downloader_by_Whonix|Tor Browser Downloader by Whonix]] to install a new version. Afterwards, Tor Browser will support the user's native language.

=== Method 2: Mozilla Firefox Add-on ===
Complete these steps in Whonix-Workstation.

'''1. Start Tor Browser'''

'''2. Check Tor Browser's Firefox ESR Version'''

<code>Tor Browser</code> -> <code>Help</code> -> <code>About Tor Browser</code>

The output should be something like: <code>45.9.0</code>.

'''3. Install a Language Pack'''

Visit https://download-origin.cdn.mozilla.net/pub/firefox/releases/45.9.0esr/linux-i686/xpi/ and install the required language pack.

Note: <code>45.9.0</code> in the above URL needs to be changed to match the Firefox ESR version Tor Browser is based on.

'''4. Restart Tor Browser'''

Tor Browser will now default to the user's native language.

